<p>You can view and copy the source of this page:
</p><textarea id="wpTextbox1" name="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" readonly="">I'm a lecturer in the Department of Computer Science at the University of Bath. My interests are more directly concerned with collaborative aspects of human-computer interaction than with software engineering. However, my research frequently span issues between the two. I am a member of the IFIP working group 2.4/13.7 on User Interface Engineering (http://www.se-hci.org/), which is centrally concerned with software architectural- and design-method pragmatics that impact on the effectiveness of interactive systems. 

Dialogue and explanation relies upon certain sets of expectations on the part of a speaker (eg a user) and a listener (eg a requirements engineer). These sets of expectations are managed rather well when phrased in terms of particular experiences. Experiences are typically related in a story-like manner.  People seem to be rather good at handling this narrative in most contexts. There is a rise of interest  in narrative tools, such as scenarios and personae, in end-user requirements analysis. I'd like to explore the limitations and benefits of extrapolating from the stories people tell to the formal descriptions that software engineers require to build useful and usable systems.
==== Details ====
'''Work:''' [http://www.bath.ac.uk/comp-sci/hci/ University of Bath, UK]

'''Email:''' l.watts at bath.ac.uk

'''Web:''' [ ]</textarea><div class='templatesUsed'>

